<paragraph id="8B833682FFDCFFB2EBF2FC0EFD89FA4C" blockId="9.[151,1437,1002,1495]" pageId="9">
South American biodiversity has always been unique (Jenkins 
<emphasis id="B948EA90FFDCFFB2E833FC08FC14FB98" box="[854,910,1002,1027]" italics="true" pageId="9">et al.</emphasis>
2013). Both the described field cricket species here validate to this point with their remarkably distinct morphological features. For example, presence of spines above subapical spurs on 
<collectionCode id="ED2DAE47FFDCFFB2EAD8FBD7FE77FBD1" box="[445,493,1075,1098]" pageId="9">TIII</collectionCode>
, which was also documented from recently described 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D01FFDCFFB2EF3DFBD6FB58FBD0" box="[1112,1218,1074,1099]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Gryllinae">Gryllinae</taxonomicName>
crickets from 
<collectingCountry id="F32B7612FFDCFFB2EE0CFBD7FA06FBD1" box="[1385,1436,1075,1098]" name="Peru" pageId="9">Peru</collectingCountry>
(Desutter-grandcolas 
<emphasis id="B948EA90FFDCFFB2EAEFFBB3FE5EFBF4" box="[394,452,1110,1135]" italics="true" pageId="9">et al.</emphasis>
2014). More than a thousand species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D01FFDCFFB2E8F2FBB2FB9BFBF4" box="[919,1025,1110,1135]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Gryllinae">Gryllinae</taxonomicName>
are known from the Old World and one of the key characters that have long been given to identify and separate this cricket group from others (like Nemobiines, long considered close to 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D01FFDCFFB2E92CFB7AFD2CFB2C" box="[585,694,1182,1207]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Gryllinae">Gryllinae</taxonomicName>
, but see Chintauan-marquier 
<emphasis id="B948EA90FFDCFFB2EF61FB7BFBACFB2C" box="[1028,1078,1182,1207]" italics="true" pageId="9">et al</emphasis>
. 2016) has been the absence of spurs on 
<collectionCode id="ED2DAE47FFDCFFB2EA65FB27FEAAFB41" box="[256,304,1219,1242]" pageId="9">TIII</collectionCode>
. Based on recent taxonomic studies there becomes an urgent need to revise the diagnostic keys for families and subfamilies (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B73FFDCFFB2EAA3FB02FC7CFB65" author="Hugel" box="[454,998,1254,1279]" pageId="9" refString="Hugel, S., DeSutter-GrandcolaS, L. (2017) SouS-ordre deS Orthoptera EnSifera (OrthoptereS EbSifereS). In Delvare, ** &amp; Aberlenc, H. P. LeS inSecteS du monde. BiodiverSite, ClaSSification, CleS de determination deS familleS. Quae, in preSS." type="book" year="2017">
Hugel and Desutter-Grandcloas, 
<quantity id="4CC49B67FFDCFFB2E822FB03FC3BFB65" box="[839,929,1255,1279]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.12318" pageId="9" unit="in" value="2017.0">
2017 
<emphasis id="B948EA90FFDCFFB2E8EEFB03FC3BFB65" box="[907,929,1255,1278]" italics="true" pageId="9">in</emphasis>
</quantity>
press
</bibRefCitation>
). Another interesting combination of characters relates to the presence of stridulum but absence tympanum as seen in 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D01FFDCFFB2EF51FAEEFAE0FAB8" authority="Jaiswara" authorityName="Jaiswara &amp; Desutter-Grandcolas" authorityYear="2017" box="[1076,1402,1290,1315]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Perugryllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="estiron" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="B948EA90FFDCFFB2EF51FAEEFA94FAB8" box="[1076,1294,1290,1315]" italics="true" pageId="9">Perugryllus estiron</emphasis>
Jaiswara
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27B57EBFFDCFFB2EEE2FAEFFF20FADD" pageId="9" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
: both sexes lack tympanum on their TI and females are completely apterous, while males possess forewing with series of teeth on the stridulatory file. This is an interesting combination of features, which would call for observation of mating behavior in this species: do males actually call? Do females locate males acoustically? Or are the forewings of the males producing other kind of mating signals (call? courtship?) that can be perceived by the females without a tympanum?
</paragraph>
